▶ ID: 111535 (38) No.4989025>>4989295

>>4988954
GATE, or Gifted and Talented Education; those of us who have been through it, and the realization that it's probably nowhere near as benign a pogram as it seems on the surface.
From Kikepedia:
>In the United States, each state department of education determines if the needs of gifted students will be addressed as a mandatory function of public education. If so, the state determines the definition of which students will be identified and receive services, but may or may not determine how they shall receive services. If a state does not consider gifted education mandatory, individual districts may, thus the definition of what gifted is varies from state or district.[36]
>In contrast with special education, gifted education is not regulated on a federal level, although recommendations by the US Department of Education are offered. As such, funding for services is not consistent from state to state, and although students may be identified, the extent to which they receive services can vary widely depending upon a state or district's budget.
>tl;dr - there are no official guidelines, and we can do whatever the fuck we want with these kids.

Continuing from the last thread, I wanted to answer a question before I get into the current topic. Anon asked how I jumped realities, so here's the story.
I was 17, about a dozen of my friends tripped acid. We all did stuff, and the night was coming to a close as we were all pretty much done tripping. We ended up all sitting in a friend's room, some people were smoking herb. My friend thought it would be fun to show off some guns, so he passed around a sawed-off shotgun he had. The shotgun went around the entire circle of friends until it got to me, I was the last one. I thought it would be fun to make the hammer click, and assumed it was unloaded since it had already been totally passed around the room. NEVER DO THIS
So I cocked the hammer and aimed it at the guy to my left, and pulled the trigger. The fucking thing went off. BOOM. The jolt of it and the loud sound made my eyes shut reflexively. I knew what I did, but I couldn't accept it. So in the darkness I sent out "feelers" like little strings in what felt like 3 (or maybe 4) dimensions, looking for some possible reality where what just happened didn't happen. Finally I hit on something, it felt "up and to the left" but far away. So I "grabbed onto it" and refused to let go. The feeling was like holding onto an innertube being pulled behind a boat, it was pulling me and almost making me lose my grip, but I wouldn't let go.
Finally the moving sensation stopped, so I opened my eyes. My shot friend was feeling his chest in a panic, the echo of the gunshot was still reverberating in the room. But in this "new" reality, the shotgun had merely hit a (stolen) stop sign that was sitting beside the couch, making the loud 'bang' noise. Everyone laughed nervously, and the friend who owned the gun said, 'Haha, that was scary, but luckily the gun was unloaded!" He opened it up, and sure enough there were two 12-gauge shells in it. Then everyone got really nervous and he put the gun away.
That's how it happened, it was mainly done with willpower and intuition, but I do the "feelers into possible realities" trick as often as I need to, when the need arises. I just usually don't pull myself into new realities, I don't think I could do it if death wasn't on the line because it introduces an element of disbelief, and if you don't KNOW you can't do it.

I remember part of the test vividly. It included a section with a bunch of squares the same size with a line underneath it, then a section with rectangles and a line under neath it, there might have been a section with circles, then there was some math and science questions if I remember correctly. The sections with the shapes required me to use the shape and draw something from that shape, then write what it was below on the line. I turned a square into a house, a spaceship, a cube, a lego brick etc. rectangles into a door, a ladder, a window, a shoe, etc. then circles into an orange, soccer ball, basket ball, bicycle wheel, gear, etc. There were about 50 of the same shape in each question, then a pattern recognition section, a logic section, and a section that showed you a 3d structure of blocks from a upper 3/4 perspective and asked what a specific side should look like.
I remember taking the test in kindergarten or first grade and being told they wanted to advance me to fourth grade immediately but my parents declined. The only thing is, there's not much at all I remember about the GATE program. I remember each year had a theme of sorts, I remember we had to read a book one time then bring a doll we each had to make and mine was really shitty. I think one day we built structures out of some cheap building materials like marshmallows and uncooked spaghetti, I was in these classes every day of elementary school and continued to be in the program up until high school graduation but I can't remember anything we did.
I also had two different scenarios where someone tried to abduct me. The one I remember best was this old hobo looking guy in a big coat on a three wheeled bicycle offered me coke (soda) and tried to get me to follow him home, then when I refused he told me if I ever had any problems to come talk to him. the others were dark sedans with tinted windows trying to lure me in. One guy would be driving, the guy in the passenger seat would talk to me and try to get me to come with them.
I'm also sharing a few things with other anons in this thread. I was born a month early but weighed much heavier than the average baby, brought in by school counselors and asked questions about my experiences at school and home every month even though I was a model student. I was born on a military base, then relocated to a small town in Texas by age 2. My dad was a Drill Instructor at the time of my birth but prior to that he was a Nuclear, Biological and Chemical warfare dude and also taught the water combat survival school, guerilla warfare course and had completed the scout sniper school in the last three months of his enlistment, among other things. I distinctly remember a few weeks after 9/11 coming home from school and seeing a big black car out in front of our house and some men in suits talking to my dad in our living room. I usually did my homework on the dinner table even with guests but my dad told me to go to my room. I asked him about it later and he said some guys had offered him his job back but he turned it down because "I'd have to go away for a long time and it would make us lots of money but then I wouldn't get to see you and your brother grow up."
Blackouts for me are rare but some thing that happens fairly often for me is almost a precognitive deja vu. Like when you see a reaction gif/image that's fairly popular but you have no idea what it's from, then months later you're watching a movie then suddenly things start a sync up, then bam there it is in vivid detail just like you've seen before and you can remember your first time seeing it with such clarity it stops you in your tracks. Except for me I'll get this precognition through dreams, usually it'll be something mundane, like sitting in a cpr class, or working on a car or writing an email on my phone in a unique place. I wake up, then forget about it, then it happens months later, exactly as I'd seen it.
I get calls often from unknown numbers that just end with a "click" immediately. Calling back the number results in a machine saying the number is not in service.
Questions for anons:
1. does picking up foreign languages come pretty easy to you?
2. were you fingerprinted had your iris scanned and picture taken by police visiting your GATE class under the guise of "This is how we solve crimes and catch bad guys" type of deal?
3. Is there a name of a place that sticks in your mind that you have never heard of, never visited and for all intents and purposes could be completely nonexistent until you looked it up on google? A name of a place that should mean nothing to you but you can't shake it?

Anons, story time.
A couple of years ago I was playing around with philosophy, religion, mathematics, and the like. The way to solve Godel's Incompleteness Theorems. Real, axiomatic Holiness.
I thought I made success. I used proof softwares, and they came back valid. I wanted to show everyone, I showed my then mathematics teacher, who told me that I should have more experience with formal education before making proposals.
I dropped out of my classes, instead trying to apply my idea to myself, to show by example. I trained, meditated, and explored myself mentally, physically and emotionally, using cannabis as a shamanistic aid. In time, my family noted that I was unusually pleasant to be around, not in the "nice personality sense," but they physically felt better around me; my father who was very ill, made note of that. At the same time, I felt beaming with energy. It was if I had harnessed an aura. I skyped which is where I know from hindsight where I fucked up with a prospective gf, and I could swear there was light around my silhouette that pulsed with my heartbeat. She even noted it, but I told her it was just glare because I wasn't prepared for what I was experiencing.
But something went wrong. Over time I was losing my capacity to explain myself clearly, like my mind was being bent. I started to have verbal word salads, my capacity to articulate was being destroyed. I was afraid that I was losing my mind, like a genetic predisposition for mental illness was taking hold (I was at the right age for that to manifest.) I tried posing on 4chan my idea before my mind completely degraded, but by then I could barely be coherent. I was reduced to silence. I stopped smoking cannabis, and braced myself for the real possibility that I was going mad.
Then, during a summer festival, I went to a drink station, and my brother offered to buy me a beer. We had been standing in line, and it was hot, so I asked for water.
The drink purveyor reached down to where he had been getting water for other customers, stopped, turned around and grabbed a water from another bin. I found that odd, but dismissed it.

▶ ID: 7ae0a2 (29) No.4991251
>>4990818
I think that might be the same thing I took and what I know about it is it's General intelligence test irrc
Found it.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G_factor_(psychometrics)
"The g factor (also known as general intelligence, general mental ability or general intelligence factor) is a construct developed in psychometric investigations of cognitive abilities and human intelligence. It is a variable that summarizes positive correlations among different cognitive tasks, reflecting the fact that an individual's performance on one type of cognitive task tends to be comparable to that person's performance on other kinds of cognitive tasks. The g factor typically accounts for 40 to 50 percent of the between-individual performance differences on a given cognitive test, and composite scores ("IQ scores") based on many tests are frequently regarded as estimates of individuals' standing on the g factor.[1] The terms general intelligence, general cognitive ability, general mental ability, or simply intelligence are often used interchangeably to refer to this common core shared by cognitive tests.[2]"

Ok, so I lived in Saudi Arabia as a kid because my dad worked for an oil company that was full of CIA spooks. When we moved back to US, they wanted to advance me 2 grades, but my parents said no because I was already young for my grade (17 at graduation). I thought it was due to superior, overseas, oil-funded education, but they put me in a program called FOCUS, then PROBE in middle school. They made me do weird shit that the other gifted kids didn't have to do like go read to kindergarteners into my senior year. Principal said it was because they didn't have a program suitable for me, so they had to augment my curriculum despite other gifted and AP courses.
Took Independent Study as a freshman in hs (for gifted kids only), and the teacher would do "games" with us on Fridays. I was the only kid who could do these computations in my head, so then the teacher administers some tests to only me that involved spatial reasoning with shapes being folded/unfolded. Got tested for months on end. Never told why, weird because already had IQ tests done in elementary and middle school.
Scored perfect on English section of SAT and ACT. Missed one question in math portions of both. US Navy suddenly starts showing up at my school and house, dad takes me to meet with them in some federal building downtown. End up taking a full academic scholarship instead. Navy reps show up at my freshman dorm, tell them to fuck off.
Brother graduates law school and is now an accomplished judge. He recently tells me that CIA kept trying to recruit him during law school. Wtf?
Also, kidnapped off strets of Saudi Arabia but my mom did some Chuck Norris, Delta force, shit and rescues me because Saudis won't help an American.
Go to a psych as an adult, find out I'm an ENFJ. Psych dr starts doing weird tests outside of normal treatment. Gives me pills that make me hear original music in my mind, but I have no musical aptitude/can't read/write music. Start seeing black cats, too, but I know it's not real. Tell dr, dr says to keep taking them. Realize drs and psych meds are shit, stop taking them.
Get my hs transcript for college class enrollment as an adult student. Been so long since graduation that county gives me full record. See my IQ is 155 with an eidetic memory. Dad later tells me he has eidetic memory, discovered during his stint in Vietnam.
Incredible lucid dreams my whole life. Flying dreams every night but not euphoric just used as mode of transportation. Can read a person in 2 seconds flat. Notice synchronicities before events. Think I may have successfully astral projected on a few occassions. Get that weird tingle all over my body when I am engaged in visual thinking. See patterns in everything like a schizophrenic would. What does it all mean? Are we crazy or just been made to feel that way via perception incompatibility?

ID: 2252ea (4) No.4992430>>4992481 >>4992492 >>4992499
holy fuck this makes me feel weird
When I was younger, I was in and out of random classes, that first were regarding a speech impediment(F and Th), but I specifically remember GATE.
In order to spin some perspective, I grew up in Buffalo, NY, actually more specifically… I grew up in Hamburg, NY. When I was younger (3 to 7), my parents had put me into programs originally to aid with my speech impediments, but later it was more-or-less to control my undiagnosed psych problems. When I was about four to five, they put me in a year of this GATE/Headstart program, and I remember quiet a bit of it for some reason.
I remember specifically that we were disallowed from bringing in our own lunches, and our lunches usually comprised of simple shit. Peanut butter, celery stick, and occasional box of raisins. Every so often we would be given cups of tea with some slice cucumbers but the tea never sat right with me. Might be thanks to living with a British mother, but I practically refuse to drink tea from anyone but from my direct family.
The tea though had a weird, almost peppermint taste. Which was another reason I avoided it. In time, my father removed me from the program stating that, "It's not good for you and I" and never has specified the reasons as to why I was fully removed.
My time at GATE comprised of a lot of weird TV shows. We had one show that oddly was about fish biology, yet it more-or-less was simplefied and watered down to the point of just explaining what certain parts of the fish were. Other times we had instances of practicing arts and craft, but that shit was geared towards making things from books like Rainbow Fish.
The one thing that sticks in my mind though was the almost medical nature of the staff. Almost all of them knew or head some background in doctor related fields. Now that I think about it, the ones that even the kids knew were involved at the Central Hospital in Buffalo(near Niggerland), were always the ones making that peppermint tea.
Well anyway, as I left that program, literally within a week of leaving it, I had a near death experience in which I was swimming in a local pool, and was pulled under by a group of older teens cannonballing into the deep end. I remember at my age of four or five just telling myself, "This is it. Prepare…" and I started to ease my body coming to terms with death. When I was slowly letting out air bubbles, I saw this old women walk up to the side of the pool in a colonial dress, and for some reason, even though I didn't know who the hell she was, I felt relieved. The thing I compare it too these days is an opiate high. I just felt so… Relieved.
This old lady pulled me out of the water and simply told me, "Things that must not be, must never occur" and set me onto the side of the pool. I passed out and probably was out for three minutes before someone finally found me drooling water out of my mouth and they shook me awake.
1/??

ID: 5a3728 (11) No.4992914>>4992987
"The half-decade following Sputnik in 1957 and the last half-decade of the 1970s may be viewed as twin peak periods of interest in gifted and talented children. Separating the peaks was a deep valley of neglect in which the public fixed its attention more eagerly on the low functioning, poorly motivated, and socially handicapped children in our schools. It was not simply a ease of bemoaning the plight of able and then disadvantaged learners, with each population taking turns as the pitied underdog or the victim of unfair play. Rather than transferring the same sentiments from one undereducated group to another, the nation found itself transforming its mood from intense anxiety to equally profound indignation: anxiety lest our protective shield of brainpower became weaker, rendering us vulnerable to challenge from without, followed by indignation over social injustice in the land, which could tear us apart from within. Now we are experiencing a revival of earlier sensitivities to the needs of the gifted. Judging from these vacillations in national temperament, it seems as if we have nor yet succeeded in paying equal attention simultaneously to our most and least successful achievers at school." -Abraham J. Tannenbaum, 1979
Keep reading the shit this guy has written, it's fucking crazy

ID: b01ad3 (14) No.4993260>>4993317 >>4993415 >>4993462 >>4993954
Gonna add more fuel to the fire here
Started G/T in 2nd grade, only one in my class because I took some test. I did this through 5th grade in both math and reading. At the end of 5th grade, met with a bunch of people and took some logic-y tests and scored extremely high, 99% percentile and all. Then had to take the SAT (full) and got something in the 1200's, almost perfect in math and meh at verbal. I specifically remember this being at Laurel High School in '00 being a child surrounded by ethnics. Went to JHU CTY camp, and it was tons of other "gifted" kids. Again, I remember very little of what we did here, except the logic part of the curriculum. Truth tables, logic puzzles, I specifically remember doing the Towers of Hanoi. There was a cafeteria that we would get lunch at, and I remember a couple times coming home feeling dizzy and thinking something was off with the food.
Did a special math program in 7th & 8th grade where we went up through algebra II & geometry on saturdays. I remember hating this, and hating being stuck with the nerdiest fuckers, so I deliberately stopped doing the work and started hanging out with neighborhood kids because I wanted friends. Dropped down to just "standard" G/T math, still 2 grade levels above.
In high school, grades started turning to shit, stopped caring. Lost a lot of weight and got in great shape, started Cross Country, Track, and weightlifting. Towards the end, suddenly cared again and got 5's on every AP test junior and senior year, 10 in all (both physics ones, and both english ones). Started smoking pot after high school with my first genuine friends, and that taught me how to be sociable and developed common sense. Made me more aware of the world around me.
Finish undergrad with decent enough grades (thanks to partying first 2 years), but successfully completed 3 bachelor degrees thanks to Math overlapping with Physics & CS. Through that process, the same friends I have now I met then, and they both had very similar experiences to mine. Came into college an athiest liberal (and voted for obongo in '08), now I'm a serious traditionalist Christian, and about as conservative as one can be.
All of the fringe shit here reeks of disinfo. Either that or some bored anons have been tripping or forgetting their schizo meds. Seeing a lot of occult posts, it would do you all well to learn the history of the occult, and how it all is a form of satanism. Not in the exoteric LARPy sense, but in the esoteric sense that you are doing exactly what caused Satan to lose favor with God: he thought himself higher than God, and that he could conjure his own divine knowledge. Parallel universes and all that crap reeks of Kaballism, and their Sephirot/Qliphot.
Getting to the point: While there are almost certainly MK aspects behind the spooky shit a lot of us experienced as children (and why we are all strangely drawn to this burmese coupon-clipping website), a simpler explanation is this: it was to turn all of us into autistes. I read through the whole Tannenbaum presentation, and one thing that popped out to me was he said gifted children have a tendency to posses a holistic world-view, and often can't separate the whole into parts. I can't say the last part applies to me, but I have a knack for figuring out given something, determining where in the big-picture it fits, particularly under changing perspectives.
This, however, is something I have developed in my adult years through reading literature, history, philosophy, and theology. Looking back, I have always had this sort of talent, because I was always building intricate shit on the fly with legos and Knex (cabinetmaker as a hobby now, ha), and using intuition could just sort of figure out how to do things. Perhaps it is that we are predisposed to this method of thought, and because of that, we are able to see who pulls the strings and why they do. Have the ability to discern Truthful knowledge, in turn leading to Correct understanding. This, then, makes us immune in a sense to the various brainwashings and dumbing down programs. Think of what /pol/ does best: connects the dots and figures out the big picture: who are the actors, why are they doing what they are doing, what is their conduit, etc.
But by turning those of us with this predisposition into autistès, focusing ONLY on math/science, we will either use our talent only for that leaving the powers that be unseen, or we will burn out and turn into degenerates, as many of my former G/T peers have.

And while I'm on the subject, the magic of yesterday is the science of today. To ancient people, the idea that you could speak to a box of plastic and metal, and somehow the sound of your voice would appear on the other side of the planet–that's magic. They didn't understand microwaves or radio waves. Yet now it's common scientific knowledge. How long ago was it that the idea of "bacteria", invisibly tiny living organisms, was ridiculous science fiction? Now it's taken for granted, but a thousand years ago, do you know what made people sick? It wasn't invisible living organisms–it was…demons.
This process will inevitably hold true, projected into the future. We talk about premonitions as "magic" or "demons", yet in the future it may be known that 4-d spacetime is simply an object to be studied, and looking into the "past" or "future" is no different than walking up a hill and looking down on the valley below. I don't recall the name GATE at all, so this may not be what you all are recalling. Perhaps you will still have something to take away, though.
I remember in kindergarden being taken to an odd-shaped and poorly- lit side-room to perform a test with colored plastic bears. I remember that the same day everybody was sitting indian-style on the floor and the teacher explained how New Years would work, moving the year to 1995 on a sign on the chalkboard. The teacher was frustrated because nobody was paying attention, however I was following her completely. Then when New Years actually arrived a few weeks later, it was moved BACKWARDS from 1995 to 1994. I called the teacher out on it saying that it was only 1995 on the board because of her demonstration weeks earlier. This pissed her off, but it stayed 1994 that New Years. This still disturbs me to this day.
I remember specific instances of being very good at math, detailed memories of finishing tests much much faster than everybody and getting everything correct, or things like being obsessed with the visual patterns in multiplication tables. Math was very easy and intuitive for me. I was put into advanced math classes in 4th grade, but the only thing I remember about them is there were 6 or 7 other kids and we were taken to a room where we learned about Roman numerals, algebraic variables, and circle math. It was a very big deal for my parents and I distinctly remember them being very proud.
However, I moved to a rural area after 4th grade and was in a different school district where they were catering to a far less intelligent local population and teaching math in a very different way. I was confused by their new ways of doing math and was often told I was doing things wrong when showing my work, which caused me to lose my trust and self-confidence in math.
I always considered myself bad at math after 5th grade and would not put effort towards math. The closest thing to math I would think about was a thought game I played whenever the teacher was boring: try to think of the very smallest thing and how it relates to the thing just larger than it, classifying where objects and their parents belong, up to the size of the universe. I did this often in 6th grade. But basically I just stopped caring about math entirely all through middle school and high school and got very poor scores to show for it.
Until taking the SAT and ACT tests.
We were told scores really mattered for which college you go to, so I actually put effort into the math on the tests, despite not intending on pursuing a math-heavy profession. I spent a lot of time on the math portion deriving the math from things I could reason to be true, through visualization and logic. I checked my answers from many angles and I presumed to have gotten most questions wrong as I didn't know the "correct ways" or vocabulary being used in the tests. When the results were in I had scored in the 1300 zone. The person administering the test was astonished and urged me to consider changing my intended major, which I completely ignored because fuck those types of people. Also, I still don't trust more elaborate math than basic algebra.
With that being said, this thread reads an awful lot like 420chan considering this is /pol/ so no bump.

Don’t banish me from your vision.

or let anger enter your hearing.
In no place, in no time, be unknowing of me.
Be alert. Don’t be ignorant of me.

and whatever he wants happens to me.
I am a silence incomprehensible

>Gnosticism was, at least briefly, in the mainstream of Christianity is witnessed by the fact that one of its most influential teachers, Valentinus, may have been in consideration during the mid-second century for election as the Bishop of Rome.3 Born in Alexandria around 100 C.E., Valentinus distinguished himself at an early age as an extraordinary teacher and leader in the highly educated and diverse Alexandrian Christian community. In mid-life he migrated from Alexandria to the Church's evolving capital, Rome, where he played an active role in the public affairs of the Church. A prime characteristic of Gnostics was their claim to be keepers of sacred traditions, gospels, rituals, and successions – esoteric matters for which many Christians were either not properly prepared or simply not inclined. Valentinus, true to this Gnostic predilection, apparently professed to have received a special apostolic sanction through Theudas, a disciple and initiate of the Apostle Paul, and to be a custodian of doctrines and rituals neglected by what would become Christian orthodoxy.4 Though an influential member of the Roman church in the mid-second century, by the end of his life Valentinus had been forced from the public eye and branded a heretic by the developing orthodoxy Church.

>>4994363
Even in his esoteric teachings, such as the parable of the mustard seed (which was only to his disciples), mentions how Faith is the essential component.
Knowledge is also not the end goal, here is a different way to think about it. Consider Goedel's Incompleteness Theorems: these state that one cannot know everything there is to know about an infinite set using a finite number of axioms. Extend and apply this to our reality: we as finite beings (in our corporeal form) can only formulate finitely many axioms, and given that God is infinite in nature (one attribute determined through reason alone), we can never know God in whole. That doesn't matter though, because knowledge isn't the end in and of itself. Knowledge begets understanding; why did things come to be as they are? why am I in this time and space with the knowledge I have? other various deeper meanings. This then begets wisdom, which is the application of this to everyday life. Seeking wisdom is what is most important, and then once acquired, we have a duty to use it to the betterment of others. Contemplating the mystical aspects of God, regardless of the nature of the contemplation, is superfluous to what we were meant to do.

DAILY REMINDER:
LISTING YOUR IQ WITHOUT PROVIDING A DIRECT SOURCE FOR IT IS FRAUDULENT
>Most/all online IQ tests are scams or completely invalid. I've taken several professional IQ tests (part of my training in learning how to administer those same tests). My score usually comes out to somewhere in the 120 neighborhood. All the online tests score me at 150 or higher. IQ tests are neither fake, nor useless. However the overall IQ score (i.e. "I have an IQ of 150!!") is near meaningless without other information, and most people don't realize that the number is a combination of a several other scores.
/////
>I took as an adult. They would not tell me my overall IQ number because they said it could not possibly be determined and if it could it would be meaningless because my scores were spread so wildly across the board on the different sections of the test. For example, I believe I scored a 95 or something on one of the mathematical reasoning sections then a 145 on one of the linguistic sections. To average out scores like that down to one final number would be meaningless.
>The professional tests are done by qualified doctors- people with PhDs. Mine took 3 days to complete and included multiple sections that tests nearly all areas of the brain. I found out things about myself that I was really surprised at. It was really interesting but expensive so I wouldn't recommend it unless you NEED to get one. Compared to an online test that takes 15 minutes I think it is pretty evident which can be taken more seriously.

>it both genes and environment
Yes of course you can't have just one or the other. The definition of a living thing is "genes expressed in an environment". The point is that there is some genetic 'goal' that living things move towards as they mature. We can think of bad environment vs good environment as things which delay proper gene expression vs things which progress it. Stressful situations regulate gene expression in a negative way because certain genes which are "luxuries" get turned off in favor of ones that are necessary to survive the stress.
While IQ is highly variable an organism's instinctual intelligence is not. That's how all organisms move towards their genetic "goal" over time rather than getting lost in their complex antagonistic environment, regardless of how they stack up intellectually. The shitheads watching ESPN 3 hours a day eating their GMO cheetos and corn pops are not necessarily held back more than us because they're stupid. They ARE their stupidity and were always destined for that kind of role in society, subservient and trusting so long as basic needs/entertainment are met. I don't mean to bash on these types I just want to highlight the very real hierarchical nature of nature. Everyone has a proper place and if you try to fuck with this you get burned, eventually.
Same goes for everyone on /pol/. We have been destined for /pol/ since the womb, it was just a matter of time. For example, If I was chad thundercock with the same brain I wouldn't be writing this post right now…but I would've found this place or something similar eventually. If you're under 25 on /pol/ it easy to think of yourself as morally superior but then you have to ask have I been truly tempted yet? I know I haven't.

ID: debe08 (13) No.4998359>>4998399 >>4998499 >>4998570 >>4998747 >>5000497
Op from first thread.
Have any of you been diagnosed with autism or any other development disorders?
I remember when I was younger that my parents were worried I wasn't making any friends. I overheard my family doctor mentioning something about 'slightly' autistic.
Took me to a psychiatrist and they asked me why I didn't make friends.
I clearly remember responding "That's because everyone's an asshole. Why would I be nice to an asshole?"
They took that as me being anti-social and prescribed me a bunch of meds in the 3rd grade.
I started GATE that year as well.
The other kids were either complete spergs, straight edge anti funs or smart asses.
I got bored with how no one liked to talk about goofy shit, so I pretended to be stupid and left GATE going into 4th grade.
While in 5th grade, I did the Connecticut Mastery Test. Scored really shitty on the linguistic part, as usual.
But I scored in the 96th percentile for science and the 98th percentile for math.
I honestly thought that math test was a practice exam.
I got a fancy letter saying I scored higher than almost 48,000 other students in Connecticut.
I confessed to playing stupid so I wouldn't have to do boring logic tests.
They had me do some IQ tests.
I did extremely horrible on the written portions, like mentally retarded horrible, leading them to think I cheated on the mastery tests. Even though I had retaken them two more times and scored perfectly each time.
But then one of the testers had me answer the questions out loud instead of writing them down.
Turns out I wasn't retarded, I just scored so high that I couldn't be tested with normal tests. My thoughts happened faster than I could write them down.
They had me take a high school equivalency test. I passed that and the SAT with flying colors. They offered to let me skip from the 5th to 9th grade.
I said no because all of family and friends bullied me into thinking I would be even weirder and I would have no social life.
To this day, the summer and following school year after 5th grade is a collection of half memories and nightmares.
I was too smart for my own good.
They tried things on me.
I remember going on a train, that had no conductor or anyone driving it.
I thought it was a dream at first, but I couldn't wake up. So, my 10 year old self was convinced it was a nightmare.
Me and a group of other kids had gotten on a train, at an unused trainyard.
But after we got on, they wouldn't let us talk.
And, there was guards for every kid that had cattle prods
-cont

>first you need to want something

Interesting threads. I'll weigh in a bit:
I was in a gifted program as a kid (I don't remember it being called "GATE") and I would get pulled from class along with a few other kids. I have literally zero recollection of anything that happened in those sessions, despite clear memories of being taken from class and being returned, and the fact that I really enjoyed being taken. (Odd that I don't remember something I enjoyed?)
I haven't thought anything of it since, really.
However, I have had the distinct feeling that my life has been carefully managed by someone; I am handed comfort and general contentedness on a silver platter (I win trivial contests regularly for a steady supply of free things and have statistically improbably good fortune in general). I have a wife, and she appears to have been conditioned for me. I suspect she is a pawn of this conspiracy to keep me contented.
However, real success eludes me. If I become too good at a job I will always begin fail inexplicably. I was in sales for a while and I was extremely good at it, almost alarmingly so, then after about a year suddenly I became totally and utterly unable to make a sale. This wasn't a gradual change, one day I was closing 90% of my dems, the next day literally 0… and it went on for weeks before I had to quit. I enjoyed that job, and the owner was looking at putting me in a leadership position in the company before I inexplicably began to lose every sale.
I feel a bit like I'm in a zoo, like I'm in an environment made as close to my natural habitat as possible, protected and cared for, but never allowed to do the things I was meant for.
I don't really have a good guess as to why this might be happening. Is it a breeding thing? My wife's family is unusual in that both sets of grandparents were orphans, so no family tree is possible. Her family is large and physically powerful: her father is 6'5, her brother is of a similar height, and both were gifted athletes. My wife and I had a son three years ago and he appears to have inherited both my mental/social aptitudes and her family's size.
